Figure 3
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="97" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Diaporthaceae" genus="Diaporthe" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Diaporthe acerigena" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="acerigena">Diaporthe acerigena</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from the phylogenetically closely related species 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. oraccinii" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" rank="species" species="oraccinii">D. oraccinii</taxonomicName>
in larger alpha conidia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="97" type="holotype">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Holotype.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
CHINA. Shaanxi Province: Qinling Mountain, on symptomatic twigs of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Acer" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Acer tataricum" order="Sapindales" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tataricum">Acer tataricum</taxonomicName>
, 27 June 2017, N. Jiang (holotype: BJFC-S1466; ex-type culture: CFCC 52554).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="97" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
Named after the host genus on which it was collected, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Acer" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Acer" order="Sapindales" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Acer</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="97" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
On PDA: Conidiomata pycnidial, globose, solitary or aggregated, deeply embedded in the medium, erumpent, dark brown to black, 185-270 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
diam, whitish translucent to cream conidial drops exuding from the ostioles. Conidiophores 14.5-17 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.4-2.9 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, cylindrical, hyaline, phiailidic, branched, straight to sinuous. Alpha conidia 7-10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.1-2.9 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
(av. = 8.6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, n = 30), aseptate, hyaline, ellipsoidal, rounded at one end, slightly apex at the other end, usually with two-guttulate. Beta conidia not observed.
</paragraph>
